ok, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Normandy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Normandy in northern France. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Americanized form of French   Normandin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Normandin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Alain, Serge, Adrien, Andre, Aurore, Celine, Clovis, Emile, Gaetan, Gilles, Laurier.","French: from a diminutive of   Normand  . Compare   Normandy  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert FitzEdith of Normandy was born in 1094, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry I King of England, was 27 and his mother, Edith Forne de Greystroke, was 10. He married Matilda d'Avranches about 1160. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 31 May 1172, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1094–31 May 1172":"1094–31. mai 1172","1094–1172":"1094–1172","1096–Female":"1096–Surnud","–1173":"–1173","1103–1219":"1103–1219","1137–1224":"1137–1224","1068–1135":"1068–1135","1084–1152":"1084–1152","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1096":"1096","1084":"1084","1172":"1172","1094":"1094","31 May 1172":"31. mai 1172","1137":"1137","1224":"1224","1103":"1103","1135":"1135","1068":"1068","about 1103":"umbes 1103","about 1137":"umbes 1137","1 December 1135":"1. detsember 1135","1219":"1219","Oxford, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England","Saint-Denis-en-Lyons, Eure, Normandy, France":"Saint-Denis-le-Ferment, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Okehampton, Devonshire, England":"Okehampton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", Donjon, Allier, France":"Le Donjon, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1094–31 May 1172":"1094–31. toukokuuta 1172","1094–1172":"1094–1172","1096–Female":"1096–Kuollut","–1173":"–1173","1103–1219":"1103–1219","1137–1224":"1137–1224","1068–1135":"1068–1135","1084–1152":"1084–1152","about 1160":"noin 1160","1152":"1152","1173":"1173","1096":"1096","1084":"1084","1172":"1172","1094":"1094","31 May 1